-- Batch 7: 4 reviews. Run this whole file as one statement.
UPDATE "Review" AS r SET "contentEn" = v.body, "titleEn" = v.title
FROM (VALUES
  ('cmnn874qr000ncndeequej97e', $grulla$Cursed spirits in Jujutsu Kaisen are naturally regarded as the source of all evil, being physical representations of human fears. However, throughout the story, the special grade cursed spirits, and especially those in the group of natural disasters, have shown us almost human motivations and goals we can identify with as an audience, such as brotherhood, a desire for justice, and sensitivity toward other beings. Even so, none of them better represents what it means to be an almost neutral entity than Hanami, who at certain moments doesn't even feel like a cursed spirit.

What's interesting about Hanami as a character is that, since she is born from the human fear of the earth's natural disasters, her main motivation, despite seeming evil at first, can be considered by some as something positive. Hanami seeks to end humanity because humanity is slowly destroying nature. In a certain sense, Hanami acts as Mother Nature's force of vengeance, and you could say she is, in a way, the karmic force and the consequence of human actions in causing climate change. In fact, it is mentioned that her cursed energy doesn't feel like that of a cursed spirit, but rather more neutral, like that of a nature spirit.

Hanami is the kind of spirit who cares about the planet that humans have been abusing for thousands of years. She wishes to kill humans to sacrifice them and thus be able to be wise in a cleaner world controlled by cursed spirits who will respect the earth. Hanami believes in Jogo's ideals along with Dagon, since they want to replace humanity with cursed spirits because they feel that curses are the true humans.

In contrast to Hanami's peaceful convictions, Mahito has encouraged them to embrace their savagery as spirits. In the middle of battle, Hanami learned to follow her instincts and began to enjoy the thrill of the fight, which allowed her to push beyond her limits.

Hanami has a close bond with her allies, and in a certain way acts as the mother of the group, even stepping into Gojo's path to save Jogo and looking after everyone behind the scenes. This aspect of her personality has earned her the affection of the other 3 disasters, and even Mahito appreciates her quite a lot.

In terms of power level, Hanami is a special grade cursed spirit with an incredibly durable body, powerful cursed techniques that can control plants, and an unusual ability to hide her presence more effectively than others. She was able to catch Gojo by surprise and momentarily take advantage of Yuji's vulnerability by using her Flower Field and a wood monster to rescue Jogo. This was possible thanks to a combination of Hanami's high intelligence as a curse, as well as her escape abilities and hidden presence. Gojo himself praised Hanami's ability to flee, since they were able to evade the strong perception of the Six Eyes. Satoru even found Hanami much more threatening than the straightforward Jogo.

Hanami possesses an incredibly durable bark around her body, capable of shattering Miwa's sword on impact. She was also able to easily ignore Kamo's Slicing Exorcism attack even though it struck the side of her head. A clean cut to Hanami's leg with Megumi's sword likewise caused no damage. Even after being struck directly in her arm by Maki using the special grade cursed tool: Playful Cloud, she was sent flying but only suffered minimal damage as a result.

After being hit several times by Maki and Megumi in her weak points, Hanami was still able to withstand their attacks, recover quickly, and ultimately overpower them with ease. The most that the majority of the students could hope to achieve was to hold Hanami off long enough for more reinforcements to arrive. Only Yuji and Todo together managed to wound Hanami enough to make her use her full power.

Additionally, due to her nature as a special grade cursed spirit, Hanami can easily reinforce her body with cursed energy to regenerate lost limbs in an instant. The recovered limbs maintain the same integrity as the rest of Hanami's incredibly durable body. She can also regenerate her weak points, the eye branches, but not if they are completely compromised and entirely separated from her body.

Hanami also has a high degree of physical strength and can easily finish off a human sorcerer in hand-to-hand combat. Once Hanami finally closed the distance between her and Kamo, it only took a few blows to incapacitate the sorcerer. But it isn't her close combat that makes her fearsome, but rather her cursed technique.

Innate cursed technique: Disaster Plants

This technique allows the user to form and control a variety of cursed flora. Normally, its abilities are initiated telepathically, activating the technique at the user's side or near a target, but it can also be deployed from the user's body.

The plants created by this technique can vary in size, shape, and physiology. It is possible to form anything from simple flowers to giant wooden roots. However, the technique's flora is still made of cursed energy, which means that curse-like plants can be created quickly and deactivated instantly.

The technique also grants the ability to absorb the life energy of real plants in a floral offering and convert it into cursed energy for the user. This ability can provide a large boost of cursed energy.

In terms of destructive power it may be the weakest of all the natural disasters' techniques; however, its versatility for stealth and its ability to recover cursed energy, combined with Hanami's physical durability, make it a perfect technique to complement the plans of the other three.

In terms of named abilities, Hanami has a wide variety of techniques, although none is especially powerful.

The roots technique creates gigantic roots from the ground and allows her to modify the battlefield terrain, although they are quite slow compared to her other techniques.

The wood ball consists of a dense, compact ball that she uses to throw her opponents and then impale them with thorns.

The cursed sprouts are perhaps her most interesting technique, since they eat the cursed energy of anyone they attach to, growing and eating more energy the more techniques their host uses.

And lastly the flower field, which she uses to distract her opponents so she can connect with her other attacks. This technique is said to be the curse's weakest.

However, we can't forget her domain expansion: the Ceremonial Sea of Light.

Hanami possesses the ability to cast Domain Expansion. The domain's guaranteed-hit ability is the beam that charges with Hanami's left arm. Hanami attempted to expand her domain during her fight against Aoi and Yuji after charging the flower on her shoulder with cursed energy. However, this was interrupted when the curtain keeping Gojo out dissipated. The technique looks fairly simple, allowing Hanami to fire a powerful beam from her shoulder and finish off her opponent in a single blow.

And don't forget Hanami's ability to use Domain Amplification, which is capable of neutralizing all cursed techniques or domains it comes into contact with. This aura or shield covers Hanami's body and even allowed her to eventually strike Gojo through his Limitless, although let's say it didn't go very well for her when she tried to use it in practice.

Despite the fact that, in my opinion, Hanami is the weakest in combat of the 4 natural disasters, her role on the team is very clear and important, being the neutral entity that keeps the others' personalities in check. Additionally, her inspiration and interpretation are the ones I like most, acting more like a karmic judgment than a simple cursed spirit that wants to kill just because. On top of that, although her techniques aren't too effective, their variety and creativity, allowing her to avoid detection even by Gojo's Six Eyes and to steal cursed energy, give her more versatility than those focused solely on destructive power, so we can't ignore this maternal entity of nature.$grulla$, $grulla$Hanami$grulla$),
  ('cmnn874hl000lcndeyvn99626', $grulla$As many of you surely know, power systems are especially interesting to me, and surely to many of you as well. Shonen tend to have innovative ability systems that deepen their characters, and they vary quite a bit in their levels of complexity. However, there is one that stands out from the rest, and that is even used as the foundation for one of the most praised shonen of the moment. Of course, I'm talking about the Nen of the acclaimed Hunter x Hunter. And what better way to begin talking about this incredibly interesting and complex power system than through the protagonist of its series, Gon Freecs.

Gon is an extremely interesting protagonist, because although he comes across as fairly typical in the early seasons, as the series matures we see how Gon begins to show his dark side more and more, until his psychological deterioration culminates in the Chimera Ant arc, specifically with Pitou and the death of Kite. Gon is easy to explain, since his techniques are quite basic for Nen techniques, and most of his combat focuses on his superhuman abilities of perception, endurance, strength, and speed, which allowed him to reach very high levels even before acquiring his Nen powers.

Gon possesses all the benefits granted by his status as a Hunter. At the start of the series, he had a fishing rod that he could wield with disconcerting precision, even managing to snatch Hisoka's tag from afar while the latter was moving at great speed. The fishing rod can also be used as an offensive weapon if the situation requires it. During the Hunter Exam, Gon was frequently praised for his observation skills, agility, and endurance. In battle, he thinks quickly to come up with alternative solutions and strategies. However, his most notable quality is the hard-to-measure and almost limitless potential with which he is gifted. Many powerful characters such as Hisoka, Wing, Biscuit, and Razor were astonished when they grasped the true magnitude of Gon's talent, which is often described as limitless. This allows him to learn extremely fast, especially in the field of Nen, where an aptitude like his is very rare. Even before learning it, he managed to use Zetsu on one occasion.

Along with his potential, it is his mental strength that continually leaves more experienced and skilled fighters perplexed, and it is a crucial component of his overflowing charisma, which draws even more powerful Hunters toward him. His indomitable will allows him to continually put his life on the line without being held back by fear, which in turn allows him to make decisions that others would never dare to make. Gon prefers to attack rather than defend, even sacrificing himself to deal damage, since his stubbornness tends to come out during combat. Because of this, he sometimes throws himself in recklessly, but at the same time he does not give up until he can no longer move. He is quite competent in hand-to-hand combat after being trained in the fundamentals of Shingen-ryu kung fu by Wing and Biscuit, as well as through natural experience. Although this quality often goes unnoticed, Gon can concentrate intensely even in the most difficult circumstances, noticing details that even Single-Star Hunters would overlook.

Other abilities he has include sleeping with a larger part of his brain awake than normal, thanks to Biscuit's training, and holding his breath for several minutes even when fatigued. After leaving Greed Island, due to his prowess in Nen, Gon became able to blend in with nature more easily, which allowed him to discover multiple new animal species at a pace that astonished Kite's companions.

Gon is an Enhancer and is therefore gifted with great strength and recovery abilities. Thanks to Biscuit's training, he has trained in at least two additional types of Nen, Emission and Transmutation, which he later refined enough to create functional Nen abilities. Originally, he displayed greater skill in Emission than in Transmutation, but by the time he met Kite in the former NGL Zone, he may have become more proficient in the latter category than in the former, as the combat potential of his Nen abilities suggests. Gon has also mastered the four basic techniques and at least five of the advanced ones (the possible exceptions being In and En, although he can use Ren to detect attacks he would otherwise be unable to react to). According to Wing, Gon's talent is found in only one out of every ten million people. He successfully performed Ten with barely any instruction, a feat Wing described as both "amazing" and "terrifying," and he learned Ren and Gyo in just one night. Under normal conditions, he was able to maintain Ren for three hours outside of combat without the slightest difficulty. With this technique, he could pulverize aura-strengthened objects thrown at him by a fellow Enhancer even in the early stages of his training. While trying to develop a Nen ability, he discovered the advanced technique Ko on his own after Wing suggested he show Tsezguerra everything he had learned at the same time, and he can deploy it quickly and in multiple parts of the body simultaneously. Likewise, he learned to use Shu simply by imagining the technique, and he succeeded on the first attempt. This means that, along with Zetsu, which he managed to use even before being introduced to the concept of Nen, this achievement qualifies him as a genius at Nen. Gon was able to discover three of the eleven techniques on his own. Although he was strictly a novice in that respect, he had some basic skill in reading an opponent's aura flow and estimating the amount deployed.

This, of course, allowed him to create his own Nen technique, the Jajanken, named after a game he plays based on the Japanese word for rock, paper, and scissors, "Janken," and the word "Jajan," or Ta da! Gon came up with the idea after learning the dangerous roots of the game within the martial arts. Jajanken consists of three parts. Gon's main attack is Rock, a simple but devastating blow that concentrates all his aura into his fist through Ko. His long-range attack is Paper, an emitted attack that fires a ball of aura from his palm; this used to be his weakest attack, the ball being somewhat slow, not very powerful, and easy to block or redirect for anyone using Ko. His mid-range attack is Scissors, a transmuted blade of aura attached to his index and middle fingers, capable of cutting through a Chimera Ant. Gon preceded each attack with the chant "First comes the rock! Rock, paper...", followed by the name of the attack. Since all three attacks were charged in the same way, Gon could decide to switch from one to another even after the preparations had begun, adapting if the opponent moved closer or backed away. Later, he became able to charge Jajanken even while running.

The long charge time made Jajanken difficult to use in real combat, although the risks it posed were the core of its power. However, through a technique called second round or Akio de, Gon is able to gather twice the normal amount of aura to use two Jajanken attacks in rapid succession, eliminating the need to perform the chant twice. The name of this technique was shouted after the first attack and immediately before the second. It is currently unclear whether Akio de was a different Nen ability or simply part of the Jajanken.

After the siege of the palace in the Chimera Ant arc, through a Contract, Gon sacrificed all of his innate talents to obtain immense power, with which he managed to defeat one of the Royal Guards, Neferpitou, on his own. He used this ability without any prior training; the only knowledge he possessed about Vows at that time came from Kurapika's explanation of his Nen ability. However, as a result, his body began to deteriorate shortly after the fight, and even after being restored to full health, Gon lost the ability to use or perceive his aura. Ging cryptically stated that Gon had only gone back to being "normal" and should consider himself fortunate, since he could have lost much more. It is currently unknown whether he can reacquire his Nen, putting an end, for the time being, to Gon's Nen abilities.

As you can see, despite the fact that Gon's technique can be summed up as a game of rock, paper, and scissors with different effects, the mechanics by which the technique works are quite complex and are rooted in how diverse and strong Nen is as a power system, so it is exactly what we needed to begin this discussion about Nen techniques. It is just a shame that we probably won't see him reach levels similar to what he showed us that fateful night with Pitou in the future.$grulla$, $grulla$Gon Freecs$grulla$),
